That's fine.

20:12.044 --> 20:14.313 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
That's your right to do that as
a reporter.

20:14.346 --> 20:18.850 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Well, let me
finally ask you,
Senator, the president said he's
open to renegotiation.

20:18.884 --> 20:23.555 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We're already hearing from
European officials
that it's -- that this is an
accord not open

20:23.589 --> 20:24.790 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
for renegotiation.

20:24.823 --> 20:28.393 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, how do you foresee moving
ahead in that
direction?

20:28.427 --> 20:30.195 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
SEN.

20:30.229 --> 20:34.466 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MIKE LEE: Well, if they're
saying this is
not open for renegotiation, and
this negotiation

20:34.499 --> 20:38.303 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
was itself something that
couldn't get through
the United States Senate, and
that's why President

20:38.337 --> 20:43.075 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Obama never submitted it to the
Senate for
treaty ratification, then we're
at an impasse,

20:43.108 --> 20:44.977 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
and we will proceed.

20:45.010 --> 20:49.715 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We will proceed, by the way, I
should add,
as a global leader in
environmental regulation.

20:49.748 --> 20:52.150 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We are a global leader in the
rule of law.

20:52.184 --> 20:56.588 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We have brought down emissions
in this country
through our legal system and
through technological

20:56.622 --> 20:57.589 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
innovation.

20:57.623 --> 20:59.224 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
We can do this on our own.

20:59.258 --> 21:02.227 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We don't have to have the
permission of countries
all over the world to do that.

21:02.261 --> 21:03.895 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
We have done it pretty well.

21:03.929 --> 21:06.798 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We have done it much better than
a lot of
our would-be partners in this
agreement.

21:06.832 --> 21:11.403 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Senator Mike Lee
of Utah, thank
you very much for talking with
us.

21:11.436 --> 21:12.404 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
SEN.

21:12.437 --> 21:15.774 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MIKE LEE: Thank you.

21:15.807 --> 21:30.522 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Brutal wars in
the Middle East,
Africa and Asia have forced the
world's populations

21:30.555 --> 21:34.226 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of refugees and displaced
persons to near
record highs.

21:34.259 --> 21:40.332 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Meanwhile, the Trump
administration has signaled
its intention to substantially
change U.S.

21:40.365 --> 21:42.134 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
refugee policy.

21:42.167 --> 21:46.571 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Filippo Grandi, who is the
United Nations'
top official leading the
response to the refugee

21:46.605 --> 21:51.576 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
crisis, is in Washington this
week for meetings
at the White House and Pentagon.

21:51.610 --> 21:54.479 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Our William Brangham sat down
with him earlier
this evening.

21:54.513 --> 21:56.348 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Hi,
Commissioner Filippo
Grandi.

21:56.381 --> 21:57.849 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Welcome.

21:57.883 --> 21:59.651 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
FILIPPO GRANDI, United Nations
High Commissioner
for Refugees: Thank you.

21:59.685 --> 22:00.886 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: You're here in
Washington,
D.C., obviously this week to
meet with some

22:00.919 --> 22:02.287 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
members of the Trump
administration.

22:02.321 --> 22:05.691 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I'm curious, what message are
you here to
convey to them?

22:05.724 --> 22:11.463 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
FILIPPO GRANDI: A message that I
have already
conveyed in previous visits.

22:11.496 --> 22:20.572 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
U.S. leadership in humanitarian
matters and
specifically in matters
concerning responses

22:20.605 --> 22:25.277 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to refugee crisis is very
important, continues
to be very important.

22:25.310 --> 22:27.412 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And the response I get is quite
good.

22:27.446 --> 22:28.747 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: What is that
response?

22:28.780 --> 22:30.615 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
What do you hear back from them?

22:30.649 --> 22:34.686 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
FILIPPO GRANDI: Well, I think we
all watched
Ambassador Haley, the U.S.
ambassador to United

22:34.720 --> 22:35.687 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Nations...

22:35.721 --> 22:37.289 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Nikki Haley,
yes.

22:37.322 --> 22:43.628 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
FILIPPO GRANDI: ... visit
recently refugee
programs in Turkey and in
Georgia.

22:43.662 --> 22:48.600 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We're talking about Syrian
refugees, the biggest
refugee crisis in the world.

22:48.633 --> 22:51.870 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And her message was very clear
and very strong.

22:51.903 --> 23:00.412 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
United States' generosity and
United States'
support for refugees continues
to be strong

23:00.445 --> 23:01.713 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
and constant.

23:01.747 --> 23:07.085 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I greatly appreciated this
message on
her part.

23:07.119 --> 23:10.956 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: I know
Ambassador Haley
has said that on several
occasions.

23:10.989 --> 23:16.428 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But we have also seen President
Trump try
to pass through an executive
order that, in

23:16.461 --> 23:20.198 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
effect, says, we're not taking
any refugees
in the U.S.

23:20.232 --> 23:25.470 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the president has conflated
refugees with
the fear of terrorism, saying,
we can't know

23:25.504 --> 23:27.506 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
who these people are.

23:27.539 --> 23:29.908 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Is this something that you bring
up with administration
officials?

23:29.941 --> 23:32.711 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Do you talk with them about
those concerns
that they have shared?

23:32.744 --> 23:35.414 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
FILIPPO GRANDI: A great deal.

23:35.447 --> 23:41.086 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In fact, I don't think there was
ever any
statement saying that no more
refugees should

23:41.119 --> 23:42.888 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
come to the United States.

23:42.921 --> 23:49.828 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There were decisions to increase
the vetting
of those selected to come here
and to limit

23:49.861 --> 23:51.263 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
certain nationalities.

23:51.296 --> 23:56.334 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
All this, as you know, is now
being discussed
in the judicial sphere.

23:56.368 --> 24:02.541 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So we have to wait for that
discussion, which
is an American, a U.S.
discussion to finish.

24:02.574 --> 24:07.512 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Our message is, resettlement
programs -- this
is what we're talking about --
are a very

24:07.546 --> 24:12.484 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
important tool to protect the
most vulnerable
refugees.

24:12.517 --> 24:18.690 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And vetting is already quite
strong for those
refugees that enter that
program.

24:18.723 --> 24:23.161 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Of course, this is a sovereign
decision of
the United States, but I think
and I hope

24:23.195 --> 24:29.634 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that, after all this is done,
after conclusions
are made, that program will be
preserved.

24:29.668 --> 24:35.307 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think it may be reduced to
previous higher
levels, but I hope that, with
the passage

24:35.340 --> 24:40.612 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of time and once these controls
-- once the
administration confident that
the controls

24:40.645 --> 24:44.816 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
are there, will we continue to
see robust
resettlement to the United
States.

24:44.850 --> 24:48.119 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: The reason I
ask about this
is, this is not just a concern
expressed by

24:48.153 --> 24:52.824 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
President Trump, but even
Chancellor Angela
Merkel in Germany has seen a
good deal of

24:52.858 --> 24:55.660 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
resistance to her very open
embrace of refugees.

24:55.694 --> 25:03.034 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There still is a very strong
fear, a conflation
of refugees with the fear of
terrorism.

25:03.068 --> 25:07.639 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I'm just curious what you --
what do you
say to world leaders when they
express this,

25:07.672 --> 25:11.977 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that we don't have the political
appetite
to take refugees onto our
shores?

25:12.010 --> 25:17.148 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
FILIPPO GRANDI: The fear of
insecurity is
a very understandable one,
especially in a

25:17.182 --> 25:25.190 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
world in which terrorism has
created so much
damage and killed so many
people.

25:25.223 --> 25:32.797 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And we are, of course, with
states in saying
controls, checks, vetting have
to be carried

25:32.831 --> 25:36.768 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
out in the most -- in the
strongest possible
way.

25:36.801 --> 25:38.270 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
This is absolutely true.

25:38.303 --> 25:41.239 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
But I also pass another message.

25:41.273 --> 25:49.548 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In fact, it's very rare, if
ever, that refuges
coming from situations of war,
of violence,

25:49.581 --> 25:53.985 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of violations of human rights
perpetrate crimes
of terrorism.

25:54.019 --> 25:55.654 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It is not they who do that.

25:55.687 --> 25:56.955 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It is other people.

25:56.988 --> 26:01.960 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
In fact, those people do not
bring terror.

26:01.993 --> 26:03.662 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Refugees flee from terror.

26:03.695 --> 26:08.166 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think it's very important not
to conflate
refugees and terrorists in this
sense.

26:08.199 --> 26:11.937 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's very important to control,
it's very
important to check, but it's
also very important

26:11.970 --> 26:16.308 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to make that distinction, and
never forget
where these people come from.

26:16.341 --> 26:19.077 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Lastly, a
quick question
on funding.

26:19.110 --> 26:22.414 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I know this is obviously an
enormous challenge
for the U.N.

26:22.447 --> 26:25.750 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Do you have enough money to do
the work you
need to do?

26:25.784 --> 26:29.087 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
FILIPPO GRANDI: Certainly not.

26:29.120 --> 26:36.061 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Our budget last year was
calculated at 7 billion
U.S. dollars, 2016.

26:36.094 --> 26:38.530 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
We got billion U.S. dollars.

26:38.563 --> 26:41.800 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So about 55 percent of our needs
the covered.

26:41.833 --> 26:44.703 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
This means that we do a lot of
prioritization.

26:44.736 --> 26:47.305 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And we prioritize, evidently.

26:47.339 --> 26:53.578 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
With so many refugee crises,
with 65 million
refugees and displaced people
around the world,

26:53.612 --> 26:56.548 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
we have to prioritize lifesaving
activities.

26:56.581 --> 26:58.383 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
What suffers?

26:58.416 --> 27:03.855 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
What suffers what is not
immediately vital
and necessary, but which is
equally important,

27:03.888 --> 27:06.591 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
like education, livelihoods.

27:06.625 --> 27:11.596 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That's why we're looking at
other ways to
meet those needs with other
sources of funding,

27:11.630 --> 27:17.268 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
because they're equally
important in the long
run to sustain assistance to
millions of refugees.

27:17.302 --> 27:19.904 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Filippo
Grandi, thank you
very much for being here.

27:19.938 --> 27:23.708 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
FILIPPO GRANDI: Thank you.

27:23.742 --> 27:34.986 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Coming up on the
"NewsHour":
new developments in the Russia
file -- Vladimir

27:35.020 --> 27:41.359 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Putin says some patriotic
Russians might have
tried to influence the U.S.
election; from

27:41.393 --> 27:48.233 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Russia to climate change, the
politics that
still divide the nation; and a
Brief But Spectacular

27:48.266 --> 27:53.138 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
take from two people living with
Alzheimer's.

27:53.171 --> 27:56.675 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But first: the double-edged
sword of urban
revival.

27:56.708 --> 28:01.246 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Even as some cities are becoming
ever more
popular and desirable, they're
also becoming

28:01.279 --> 28:07.719 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
places where the middle-class
and lower-income
residents are getting priced out
of the market.

28:07.752 --> 28:10.321 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Economics correspondent Paul
Solman has the
story.

28:10.355 --> 28:13.558 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's part of his weekly series,
Making Sense.

28:13.591 --> 28:20.031 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Looking down on
Manhattan's old
meatpacking district, the High
Line, a mecca

28:20.065 --> 28:25.370 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
for more than seven million
eager tourists
a year, astride a once-derelict
spur of the

28:25.403 --> 28:27.305 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
New York Central.

28:27.338 --> 28:29.340 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
RICHARD FLORIDA, Author, "The
New Urban Crisis":
This was an old, broken-down,
abandoned rail

28:29.374 --> 28:30.508 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
line, elevated rail line.

28:30.542 --> 28:34.446 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
PAUL SOLMAN: A rail line
shrouding the buildings
beneath.

28:34.479 --> 28:38.249 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
As a result, rents were cheap
and the cutting-edge
marginalized moved in.

28:38.283 --> 28:41.753 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
RICHARD FLORIDA: Much of this
area of Chelsea
was historically a gay
neighborhood.

28:41.786 --> 28:47.692 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And they were gay men and wanted
to do something
which celebrated the history of
the old gay

28:47.726 --> 28:48.693 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
neighborhood.

28:48.727 --> 28:51.463 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Noted urbanologist
Richard Florida:

28:51.496 --> 28:54.432 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
RICHARD FLORIDA: There's one of
the old buildings
still with the rainbow flag.

28:54.466 --> 28:59.070 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: A remnant of a past
that proved
a harbinger of gentrification to
come.

28:59.104 --> 29:02.907 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
RICHARD FLORIDA: Once they built
the park,
it became a draw, not of people,
but for real

29:02.941 --> 29:04.209 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
estate developers.

29:04.242 --> 29:05.944 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And they never anticipated that.

29:05.977 --> 29:10.982 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
No one anticipated the High Line
would be
a place that luxury towers would
grow up around.

29:11.015 --> 29:12.951 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: But have they ever.

29:12.984 --> 29:18.656 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
For nearly a mile-and-a-half,
the elevated
walkway now winds through towers
full of luxury

29:18.690 --> 29:25.630 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
condos, over-the-top testimony
to the urban
revitalization that Florida
famously championed

29:25.663 --> 29:28.366 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
in his 2002 book, "The Creative
Class."

29:28.399 --> 29:31.503 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
RICHARD FLORIDA: We're going
through, I think,
one of the greatest economic
transformations

29:31.536 --> 29:37.008 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
in history, from an old
industrially, corporate-based
vertical economy to a new
knowledge economy.

29:37.041 --> 29:40.345 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But the twist I try to add is,
it's also urban.

29:40.378 --> 29:41.346 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
It's city-based.

29:41.379 --> 29:42.347 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It's clustered in cities.

29:42.380 --> 29:45.016 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Florida's twist
became gospel.

29:45.049 --> 29:50.221 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Attract members of the creative
class, and
they, in turn, will create jobs,
which will,

29:50.255 --> 29:52.791 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
in turn, renew and rebuild.

29:52.824 --> 29:53.892 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
And it happened.

29:53.925 --> 29:55.794 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Just look at the High Line.

29:55.827 --> 30:01.299 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But what Florida now sees is the
double edge
of the advice he gave, and that
so many followed.

30:01.332 --> 30:05.870 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
RICHARD FLORIDA: A bigger,
denser city in
general increases the rate of
innovation,

30:05.904 --> 30:08.506 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
increases the rate of start-up,
increases
the rate of productivity.

30:08.540 --> 30:12.610 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
At the same time, the bigger,
the denser,
the more knowledge-intensive
increases the

30:12.644 --> 30:17.115 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
rate of inequality, increases
the rate of
economic segregation, makes
housing less affordable.

30:17.148 --> 30:18.817 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
So it's a two-sided monster.

30:18.850 --> 30:23.388 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Those unintended
consequences
of urban revival are the
real-world twist

30:23.421 --> 30:26.958 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Florida wrestles with in his
latest book,
"The New Urban Crisis."

