is simply
go along with the investigation.

49:15.986 --> 49:18.722 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Do not comment on the
investigation.

49:18.755 --> 49:21.525 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Don't do anything that makes it
look like
you're putting any pressure on
the investigation.

49:21.558 --> 49:25.395 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I understand the president and
his team are
frustrated because they don't
see any there

49:25.429 --> 49:26.630 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
there.

49:26.663 --> 49:28.498 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But I think they need to do
that.

49:28.532 --> 49:31.969 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think, as far as the staff is
concerned,
I think it was absurd that the
Russian delegation

49:32.002 --> 49:35.038 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
was able to go into the Oval
Office with recording
devices and cameras.

49:35.072 --> 49:37.140 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They didn't know who was going
to get the
photos.

49:37.174 --> 49:40.777 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The Keystone Cops part of this
must end.

49:40.811 --> 49:45.849 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
With an outsider president and
an investigation
going on, the staff has to be
twice as good,

49:45.882 --> 49:47.651 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and they can't afford to make
these kind of
mistakes.

49:47.684 --> 49:50.921 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And, Karine, no
matter what
is going on in the White House,
if Donald

49:50.954 --> 49:55.459 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Trump's base, the people who
voted for him,
like the basics of what he's
doing, whether

49:55.492 --> 50:01.198 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
it's the climate decision or, I
don't know,
his attempts to set up a travel
ban, even

50:01.231 --> 50:06.003 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
though that hasn't happened yet,
does it really
matter politically whether the
White House

50:06.036 --> 50:07.337 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
is -- quote -- "dysfunctional"
or not?

50:07.371 --> 50:09.706 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
KARINE JEAN-PIERRE: I think it
will at some
point.

50:09.740 --> 50:12.175 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I mean, there's 2018 coming
right around the
corner.

50:12.209 --> 50:16.446 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And that's going to hurt
Republicans, what
we see Donald Trump doing,
because it's not

50:16.480 --> 50:17.714 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
just Republicans.

50:17.748 --> 50:21.318 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's not that small base that
got him to the
White House.

50:21.351 --> 50:24.321 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It was also Democrats and
independents that
got him into the White House.

50:24.354 --> 50:25.322 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MATT SCHLAPP: That's true.

50:25.355 --> 50:27.190 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(CROSSTALK)

50:27.224 --> 50:27.824 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MATT SCHLAPP: And, by the way,
he has a lot
of them on his staff at the
White House, too.

50:27.858 --> 50:28.825 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
KARINE JEAN-PIERRE: Right.

50:28.859 --> 50:30.560 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
But here's the thing.

50:30.594 --> 50:32.896 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
If you look at the House in some
of these
suburbs that they have to win,
the Republicans

50:32.929 --> 50:36.600 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
have to win, you need support
outside of your
Republican base.

50:36.633 --> 50:38.502 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, it is going to hurt them
when it comes
to 2018.

50:38.535 --> 50:41.738 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: I have a feeling
this may not
be the last time we have a
chance to talk

50:41.772 --> 50:42.739 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
about this.

50:42.773 --> 50:43.740 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

50:43.774 --> 50:45.108 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MATT SCHLAPP: Let's hope not.

50:45.142 --> 50:47.077 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Karine
Jean-Pierre, Matt Schlapp,
thank you both.

50:47.110 --> 50:52.315 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MATT SCHLAPP: Thank you.

50:52.349 --> 50:57.587 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
KARINE JEAN-PIERRE: Thanks,
Judy.

50:57.621 --> 51:04.227 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Now to another in
our Brief
But Spectacular series, where we
ask people

51:04.261 --> 51:06.229 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
to describe their passions.

51:06.263 --> 51:11.668 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Five-and-a-half million
Americans are living
with Alzheimer's disease, and
another 15 million

51:11.701 --> 51:14.004 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
serve as their unpaid
caregivers.

51:14.037 --> 51:20.644 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Tonight, two individuals
diagnosed with Alzheimer's,
Chris Hannafan and Pam Montana,
share their

51:20.677 --> 51:21.778 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
experiences.

51:21.812 --> 51:23.380 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CHRIS HANNAFAN, Living With
Alzheimer's: I
am 66.

51:23.413 --> 51:26.016 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I was diagnosed when I was 65.

51:26.049 --> 51:35.625 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
PAM MONTANA, Living With
Alzheimer's: I was
diagnosed initially in November
of 2015.

51:35.659 --> 51:37.160 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And I think I'm getting the
dates right.

51:37.194 --> 51:39.963 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Part of my issue is my dates
sometimes mush
together.

51:39.996 --> 51:42.599 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CHRIS HANNAFAN: Yes, I know
exactly what we're
doing.

51:42.632 --> 51:43.733 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I know you're Steve.

51:43.767 --> 51:44.768 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I know you're Zack.

51:44.801 --> 51:47.304 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We're here in Pine Street,
finally.

51:47.337 --> 51:49.272 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

51:49.306 --> 51:55.979 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAM MONTANA: On July 20 of last
year, I received
the official diagnosis, with 17
research physicians

51:56.012 --> 52:02.486 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and doctors in the room, myself,
my husband
and my two children, with the
diagnosis of

52:02.519 --> 52:06.356 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
early-onset, early-stage
Alzheimer's.

52:06.389 --> 52:11.061 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
QUESTION: You can take a minute
or two.

52:11.094 --> 52:13.897 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
PAM MONTANA: Every time I say
it.

52:13.930 --> 52:22.539 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CHRIS HANNAFAN: The way I
explain it to people
is, I am in a new life.

52:22.572 --> 52:26.510 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
My former life no longer exists,
and it's
up to me to create a new life.

52:26.543 --> 52:28.578 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
PAM MONTANA: I knew something
was wrong.

52:28.612 --> 52:31.214 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's not normal to not be able
to calculate
a tip anymore.

52:31.248 --> 52:35.418 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's not normal to not do math
in your head
and to be able to subtract or
add numbers.

52:35.452 --> 52:40.991 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's not normal to not remember
conversations
or to attend a training class
and not remember

52:41.024 --> 52:42.159 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
what was taught.

52:42.192 --> 52:44.794 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CHRIS HANNAFAN: More and more
words are going
away.

52:44.828 --> 52:51.801 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And there are a number of words
that, no matter
how I remember them, they are
not there.

52:51.835 --> 52:56.406 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I could say, OK, now I have got
it, and, two
minutes later, I won't have it.

52:56.439 --> 52:59.976 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAM MONTANA: With Alzheimer's,
you don't have
an option.

53:00.010 --> 53:01.344 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
You just -- it's just not there.

53:01.378 --> 53:03.146 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
The information is just gone.

53:03.180 --> 53:07.217 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CHRIS HANNAFAN: It seems to be
particularly
difficult for those of us with
Alzheimer's

53:07.250 --> 53:14.958 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
early-onset to have -- sorry --
I got a little
bit.

53:14.991 --> 53:18.428 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
OK, where was I?

53:18.461 --> 53:21.831 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAM MONTANA: Frustrating is the
word that
comes to mind.

53:21.865 --> 53:27.237 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I am frustrated with the fact
that I don't
know what 32 minus seven is
without a pen

53:27.270 --> 53:28.872 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
and paper.

53:28.905 --> 53:32.375 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It frustrates me that I have no
idea what
today is, but I do know it's
Friday.

53:32.409 --> 53:34.744 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CHRIS HANNAFAN: The first thing
I lost was
my car.

53:34.778 --> 53:39.616 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, I was no longer able to use
my car for
various reasons.

53:39.649 --> 53:42.219 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
I got a bicycle.

53:42.252 --> 53:43.987 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And I have had two crashes with
that.

53:44.020 --> 53:45.789 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And I think part of that is
spatial.

53:45.822 --> 53:48.024 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
PAM MONTANA: Now I have a new
job.

53:48.058 --> 53:53.897 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that job is to be loud and
proud about
my disease, to share my symptoms
with everyone

53:53.930 --> 53:55.498 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and anyone who will listen to
me.

53:55.532 --> 53:57.601 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
CHRIS HANNAFAN: I'm able to be
useful.

53:57.634 --> 54:05.375 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I'm able to have -- to surround
myself with
a lot of people, which is
absolutely the most

54:05.408 --> 54:06.977 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
important thing you can do with
Alzheimer's.

54:07.010 --> 54:09.713 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAM MONTANA: Everyone always
tells me I look
good.

54:09.746 --> 54:13.049 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Well, what does that have to do
with anything?

54:13.083 --> 54:17.621 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I keep saying to people, I'm
going to walk
around in a bathrobe with a
towel on my head,

54:17.654 --> 54:22.826 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
you know, no makeup, just an old
hag, and
then maybe then they will think
I have Alzheimer's.

54:22.859 --> 54:25.295 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But this is what Alzheimer's
looks like.

54:25.328 --> 54:26.296 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It looks like me.

54:26.329 --> 54:28.064 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
CHRIS HANNAFAN: My name is Chris
Hannafan.

54:28.098 --> 54:30.500 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
PAM MONTANA: My name is Pam
Montana.

54:30.533 --> 54:33.036 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
And this is my Brief But
Spectacular take...

54:33.069 --> 54:35.105 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
CHRIS HANNAFAN: Brief But
Spectacular take.

54:35.138 --> 54:37.040 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
PAM MONTANA: ... on living with
Alzheimer's.

54:37.073 --> 54:43.780 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Thank you, Chris
and Pam, for
sharing with all of us what
you're going through.

54:43.813 --> 54:44.781 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Wow.

